issue.title: PushSecret corrupts data when pushing binary data to Hashicorp Vault

labels.name: kind/bug
labels.description: Categorizes issue or PR as related to a bug.

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
When pushing binary data from Kubernetes Secret to hashicorp Vault. binary data get corrupted. The operation end successfully, but the resulting data in Vault, though binary, are twice the size.

**To Reproduce**
Have a Secret with a binary key. Create a PushSecret like this:

```yaml
apiVersion: external-secrets.io/v1alpha1
kind: PushSecret
metadata:
  name: internal
  namespace: ictslogmgmt-elk-test
  finalizers:
    - pushsecret.externalsecrets.io/finalizer
spec:
  data:
    - conversionStrategy: None
      match:
        remoteRef:
          remoteKey: logmgmt-kafka-ingest-test/internal/kafka
  deletionPolicy: Delete
  refreshInterval: 3h0m0s
  secretStoreRefs:
    - kind: SecretStore
      name: vault-internal
  selector:
    secret:
      name: kafka-internal
  updatePolicy: Replace
status:
  conditions:
    - lastTransitionTime: '2025-07-23T12:12:53Z'
      message: PushSecret synced successfully
      reason: Synced
      status: 'True'
      type: Ready
```

While the original Secret binary data key is 18010 bytes in size, the resulting data in Vault have 33466 bytes. Text data are OK, however.

**Expected behavior**
Binary data should be stored exactly as they are. Optionally, have a way to base64 encode those along the way (and decode them in ExternalSecret CR when picking those up from Vault).

Using External Secrets operator version 0.18.2

comment.body:
> Then, while for vault this will work because vault only supports marshable data - what do we do when it comes to other providers? After all, PushSecret is a shared spec, and this feature would (IMO) be implemented at the controller level, as opposed to the provider level.

My expectation is that we keep the encoding story parallel to https://github.com/external-secrets/external-secrets/blob/main/docs/guides/decoding-strategy.md?plain=1 and that means that we would define encodingStrategy on Key Level and on Object Maps. (https://github.com/external-secrets/external-secrets/blob/main/pkg/utils/utils.go#L260 only works with individual values, but https://github.com/external-secrets/external-secrets/blob/main/pkg/utils/utils.go#L248 is there for Maps). 

For me that means data[*].match.encodingStrategy should encode whatever is returned from the ref, if it is a value, it encodes the value, if it is an object map it returns an automatically JSON encoded version in Base64. To accomodate this, we could have multiple settings:

```
encodingStrategy: None
```
could behave as we have it now and be the default. I am assuming we already do JSON encoding here based on the source

```
encodingStrategy: Base64
```

would be everything from None, just pushed through a Base64 Encoder. There could also be a difference between `Base64Object` and `Base64Values`.

I think we should make encoding behavior depend on returned values from the match. Alternatively we can think of adding more formatting options with a more flexible design but then I need to know how flexible exactly we want to make it before we push a design proposal. (i.e. should we make it possible to encode only partial values from object data, etc.)

issue.title: [Feedback] Network Console will be removed in Edge 143
issue.body:
Starting with Edge 143, the Network Console tool will be removed from Edge DevTools with no replacement. As our team shifts focus toward delivering more stable features and improving alignment with Chrome, we no longer have the capacity to maintain this tool. We recommend using the REST Client extension for VS Code for API development and testing.

If this feature is important to your workflow, we encourage you to share your feedback. Strong interest could help motivate bringing it to Chromium in the future.

comment.body:
This is a profoundly disappointing and developer-hostile decision.
The justification that this removal is for "improving alignment with Chrome" is completely backward. You had a feature that made Edge's DevTools superior to Chrome's‚Äîa genuine competitive advantage‚Äîand your solution is to remove it? That's not alignment; that's regression. True leadership would be to champion this feature and contribute it upstream to the Chromium project, not to abandon a tool your users clearly value.
Telling us to "use the REST Client extension for VS Code" shows a fundamental misunderstanding of a developer's workflow. The entire purpose and power of the DevTools Network Console is its integration. I can inspect a failed API call, right-click, edit it, and resend it immediately, all within the same context, without ever leaving the browser. It is seamless for quick, iterative debugging.
Forcing a context switch to a completely different application like VS Code for this task is a massive step backward. It kills productivity and turns a 10-second task into a multi-minute chore of copying cURL commands or manually recreating requests. Your proposed alternative is not a replacement; it's a workflow impediment.
And the excuse of not having the "capacity to maintain this tool" is frankly unacceptable coming from Microsoft. This isn't a passion project; it's a core tool for the developers you want to attract to your platform. If the community shows strong interest‚Äîwhich it clearly is‚Äîthe response should be to allocate capacity, not to surrender.
Do not remove the Network Console. This decision actively makes your product worse and disregards the real-world efficiency of the developers using it. Reconsider this.
